.SS Overview
.TS
box center;
l|l|l.
T{
Platform
T}	T{
Warning without signing
T}	T{
Mitigation
T}
_
T{
\fBWindows\fP
T}	T{
SmartScreen: \(dqWindows protected your PC\(dq / \(dqUnknown publisher\(dq
T}	T{
Authenticode code signing with a certificate from a trusted CA
T}
_
T{
\fBmacOS\fP
T}	T{
Gatekeeper: \(dqunidentified developer\(dq / \(dqcannot be opened\(dq
T}	T{
Code sign with a Developer ID Application certificate and notarise
T}
.TE
.sp
Linux binaries are not signed in the same way; only Windows and macOS are covered here.
.SS Windows: Authenticode Signing
.SS Obtain a Certificate
.INDENT 0.0
.IP 1. 3
Buy an \fBOV (Organisation Validation)\fP or \fBEV (Extended Validation)\fP code\-signing certificate
from a public CA (e.g. DigiCert, Sectigo, SSL.com). EV certificates build SmartScreen reputation
faster.
.sp
For \fBtesting or internal use\fP, create a self\-signed code\-signing certificate with \fBmakecert\fP,
\fBcertreq\fP, or PowerShell. Users will still see a warning unless they install the root in their
trust store.
.IP 2. 3
Export the certificate (and private key) as a \fBPFX (.pfx / .p12)\fP file. Note the password.
.IP 3. 3
\fI(Optional)\fP Choose an RFC 3161 timestamp server (e.g.
\fBhttp://timestamp.digicert.com\fP, \fBhttp://timestamp.sectigo.com\fP) so signatures remain valid
after the certificate expires.
.UNINDENT
.SS GitHub Secrets
.sp
Add these as \fBrepository\fP or \fBorganisation\fP secrets:
.TS
box center;
l|l.
T{
Secret name
T}	T{
Description
T}
_
T{
\fBWINDOWS_SIGNING_CERTIFICATE\fP
T}	T{
Base64\-encoded PFX file (e.g. output of \fBbase64 \-w0 cert.pfx\fP)
T}
_
T{
\fBWINDOWS_SIGNING_PASSWORD\fP
T}	T{
Password for the PFX
T}
.TE
.sp
Optional:
.TS
box center;
l|l.
T{
Secret name
T}	T{
Description
T}
_
T{
\fBWINDOWS_TIMESTAMP_URL\fP
T}	T{
RFC 3161 timestamp server URL
T}
.TE
.sp
The generated workflow step will only run when \fBWINDOWS_SIGNING_CERTIFICATE\fP is non\-empty. If the
secret is absent, Windows binaries are built unsigned (the current default behaviour).
.SS macOS: Code Signing and Notarisation
.SS Prerequisites
.INDENT 0.0
.IP 1. 3
\fBEnrol in the Apple Developer Program.\fP
.IP 2. 3
\fBCreate a Developer ID Application certificate\fP in Certificates, Identifiers & Profiles.
Download and install it in Keychain Access, then export as a \fB\&.p12\fP file with a password.
.IP 3. 3
\fBCreate an app\-specific password\fP in your Apple ID account under Sign\-In and Security →
App\-Specific Passwords.
.IP 4. 3
\fBNote your Team ID\fP from the Apple Developer membership page or Xcode.
.IP 5. 3
\fBNote the signing identity\fP string, typically
\fBDeveloper ID Application: Your Name (TEAM_ID)\fP\&.
.UNINDENT
.SS GitHub Secrets
.sp
Add these as \fBrepository\fP or \fBorganisation\fP secrets:
.TS
box center;
l|l.
T{
Secret name
T}	T{
Description
T}
_
T{
\fBAPPLE_SIGNING_CERTIFICATE\fP
T}	T{
Base64\-encoded .p12 file
T}
_
T{
\fBAPPLE_SIGNING_PASSWORD\fP
T}	T{
Password for the .p12
T}
_
T{
\fBAPPLE_SIGNING_IDENTITY\fP
T}	T{
Full code\-signing identity string
T}
_
T{
\fBAPPLE_ID\fP
T}	T{
Apple ID email used for notarisation
T}
_
T{
\fBAPPLE_APP_SPECIFIC_PASSWORD\fP
T}	T{
App\-specific password for that Apple ID
T}
_
T{
\fBAPPLE_TEAM_ID\fP
T}	T{
Team ID (10\-character string)
T}
.TE
.sp
The generated workflow steps will only run when \fBAPPLE_SIGNING_CERTIFICATE\fP is non\-empty. If the
secret is absent, macOS binaries are built unsigned.
.SS Customising Secret Names
.sp
By default Wiswa uses the secret names listed above. If your repository or organisation uses
different names, override them in \fB\&.wiswa.jsonnet\fP under the \fBgithub.secret_vars\fP key:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
{
  github+: {
    secret_vars+: {
      windows+: {
        signing_certificate: \(aqMY_WIN_CERT\(aq,
        signing_password: \(aqMY_WIN_PASS\(aq,
        timestamp_url: \(aqMY_WIN_TS_URL\(aq,
      },
      apple+: {
        signing_certificate: \(aqMY_APPLE_CERT\(aq,
        signing_password: \(aqMY_APPLE_PASS\(aq,
        signing_identity: \(aqMY_APPLE_IDENTITY\(aq,
        apple_id: \(aqMY_APPLE_ID\(aq,
        app_specific_password: \(aqMY_APPLE_APP_PASS\(aq,
        team_id: \(aqMY_APPLE_TEAM\(aq,
      },
    },
  },
}
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS How It Works
.sp
When the PyInstaller workflow is generated by Wiswa and the corresponding secrets are set:
.sp
\fBWindows\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.IP 1. 3
The base64\-encoded PFX is decoded to a temporary file.
.IP 2. 3
Each \fB\&.exe\fP in \fBdist/\fP is signed with \fBsigntool\fP\&.
.IP 3. 3
If a timestamp URL secret is set, the signature is timestamped.
.IP 4. 3
The temporary PFX file is removed.
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBmacOS\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.IP 1. 3
The base64\-encoded .p12 is imported into a temporary keychain.
.IP 2. 3
Each binary in \fBdist/\fP is signed with \fBcodesign \-\-options runtime\fP (Hardened Runtime).
.IP 3. 3
The signed binaries are submitted to Apple\(aqs notary service with \fBxcrun notarytool\fP\&.
.IP 4. 3
The notary ticket is stapled to each binary with \fBxcrun stapler\fP\&.
.IP 5. 3
The temporary keychain and certificate file are cleaned up.
.UNINDENT
